our society. This important book addresses the crucial nexus between the lived experience of inequality and how it shapes political responses. With contributors from the UK and Continental Europe, the book compiles case studies with theoretically informed discussions of the relationship between affective polarisation, social inequality and the fall-out from Brexit and COVID-19. Using a broad concept of social inequality, the book incorporates aspects of economy and society, language and emotion culture as well as interviews and film in historical and transnational perspective. The contributors offer a powerful examination of the ways in which the politics of the UK and the lived experiences of its residents have been reframed in the first decades of the 21st century.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aEqualityzGreat Britain. 0aPolarization (Social sciences)zGreat Britain. 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / Political Ideologies / General.2bisacsh1 aButterfield, Harvey, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCant, Sarah, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aChiocchetti, Paolo, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aEbrey, Jill, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aForkert, Kirsten, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFransham, Mark, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGlucksberg, Luna, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGlyn, Ifor ap, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGohrisch, Jana, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGohrisch, Jana, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aGrünkemeier, Ellen, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.